---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Roles of Tools, Resources & Prompts — AI Agent Puzzle"
  description="MCP officially splits server capabilities into three: tools let the model do things, resources show data to the model, and prompts hand workflow templates to the model. Get this distinction right first, and your own MCP server designs will hold up much better later."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container ai-agent-primitives">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Not Everything Should Be a Tool</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          Earlier we learned that an AI agent can connect to many tools, but <strong>shouldn't have all of them open at once</strong>. Now we step one further — to a more fundamental question.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Even if I only open a few capabilities, should each one be a <strong>tool</strong>, a <strong>resource</strong>, or a <strong>prompt</strong>?
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This question matters. Because when many beginners first encounter MCP, they naturally <strong>turn everything into a tool</strong>. The result:
      </p>
      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>Capabilities feel jumbled</li>
        <li>The list of tool names keeps growing</li>
        <li>The AI easily picks the wrong one</li>
        <li>Humans gradually lose track of what the system is even doing</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        MCP officially never intended to cram everything into tools — it splits server features <strong>into three: tools, resources, and prompts</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: 3 primitives at a glance -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Conclusion First: Three Things Doing Three Different Jobs</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The MCP docs are clear about how the three split up:
      </p>

      <div class="primitive-grid">
        <article class="primitive-card primitive-card--tool">
          <p class="primitive-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">✋</p>
          <p class="primitive-card__tag">model-controlled</p>
          <h3 class="primitive-card__name"><code>tools</code></h3>
          <p class="primitive-card__role">Let the model do things</p>
          <p class="primitive-card__desc">
            Let the model interact with external systems — query a database, call an API, run a calculation. <strong>The model decides on its own whether to invoke them.</strong>
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="primitive-card primitive-card--resource">
          <p class="primitive-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">📁</p>
          <p class="primitive-card__tag">application-driven</p>
          <h3 class="primitive-card__name"><code>resources</code></h3>
          <p class="primitive-card__role">Show data to the model</p>
          <p class="primitive-card__desc">
            Data and context that the server provides to the model — files, database schemas, app info. <strong>Each resource has its own URI.</strong>
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="primitive-card primitive-card--prompt">
          <p class="primitive-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">📋</p>
          <p class="primitive-card__tag">user-controlled</p>
          <h3 class="primitive-card__name"><code>prompts</code></h3>
          <p class="primitive-card__role">Hand workflows to the model</p>
          <p class="primitive-card__desc">
            Prompt templates the server provides, with parameters, so users or interfaces can <strong>kick off a workflow in a fixed format</strong>.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight-card highlight-card--strong">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          So the most important sentence on this page is:<br/>
          <strong>Not every capability should be a tool.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Why this page matters -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Why This Page Matters</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The most common mistake beginners make is: <strong>seeing "AI can call tools" and turning everything into a tool</strong>. But that quickly makes the system heavier than it needs to be. For example:
      </p>

      <ol class="misuse-list">
        <li class="misuse-item">
          <div class="misuse-body">
            <p class="misuse-title">A course rubric</p>
            <p class="misuse-desc">It's just static data, but gets turned into some odd <code>tool</code>.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="misuse-tag">Should be a resource</span>
        </li>
        <li class="misuse-item">
          <div class="misuse-body">
            <p class="misuse-title">A report template</p>
            <p class="misuse-desc">It's just a fixed format, but gets wrapped into a giant "generate-the-report" <code>tool</code>.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="misuse-tag">Should be a prompt</span>
        </li>
        <li class="misuse-item">
          <div class="misuse-body">
            <p class="misuse-title">A table schema</p>
            <p class="misuse-desc">Originally just an explanation for the model, but gets turned into something executable.</p>
          </div>
          <span class="misuse-tag">Should be a resource</span>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          And in the end: <strong>the work that prompts and resources should be doing all gets stuffed into tools.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Once you internalize this distinction, <strong>your designs will be much steadier when you start building your own MCP servers</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Tool -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">First Up — Tool: Things That Actually Take Action</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The most direct way to think about a tool is:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>It actually takes action.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        MCP defines tools as: <strong>capabilities the server exposes that a model can invoke</strong>, allowing the model to interact with external systems — query a database, call an API, run a calculation. The docs also note that tools lean toward being <strong>model-controlled</strong> — the model can decide based on context whether to call them.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So if a capability really does these kinds of things, it's usually a good fit as a tool:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Create a page</li>
        <li>Update a page</li>
        <li>Send a request</li>
        <li>Add a record</li>
        <li>Change a status</li>
        <li>Call some API</li>
        <li>Run a search and return results</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          You can think of a tool as the "<strong>hand</strong>." It's not for offering background knowledge — it's for <strong>actually doing things</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Resource -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Next — Resource: Background Material for the Model</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A resource's role is more like:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>Showing context to the model.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The MCP docs say it clearly: resources are <strong>data sources the server provides to the model</strong> — files, database schemas, app info, and more — and <strong>each resource has its own URI</strong>. The docs also note that resources lean toward being <strong>application-driven</strong>: the host app or system decides how to bring this context in.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        These things usually don't need to "execute" — they just need to "<strong>be read</strong>." So great fits for resources include:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Course rubrics</li>
        <li>Project grading criteria</li>
        <li>Notion database field descriptions</li>
        <li>Fixed configuration for a project</li>
        <li>Internal organizational naming conventions</li>
        <li>API schemas</li>
        <li>Table column definitions</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          If a tool is like the "hand," a resource is more like the "<strong>reference folder</strong>."
        </p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="sub-heading">Why a table schema is closer to a resource than a tool</h3>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Many people, when they see a table schema, instinctively think: "Should I just make an <code>explain_schema()</code> tool?" But the more natural approach is usually: <strong>treat the schema as a resource</strong>.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The reason is simple. The essence of a schema isn't "doing something" — it's <strong>"telling the model what this world looks like"</strong>. It provides background knowledge, not external action. The MCP docs describe resources in exactly this direction: providing context / data.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So if you have URI-style data sources like these, they fit naturally as resources:
      </p>
      <ul class="uri-list">
        <li><code>database://course/final-project/schema</code></li>
        <li><code>notion://rubric/final-project</code></li>
        <li><code>course://rules/writing-style</code></li>
      </ul>

      <!-- Section: Prompt -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Next — Prompt: Workflows and Formats as Reusable Templates</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Here, "prompt" <strong>isn't the casual "the sentence I type to AI"</strong> — it's a <strong>discoverable, parameterized prompt template</strong> exposed by the server.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The MCP docs are clear: prompts let the server provide structured messages and instruction templates. Clients can list available prompts, retrieve their contents, and pass parameters to customize them. And prompts lean toward being <strong>user-controlled</strong> — closer to the user actively choosing whether to use them.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So prompts are best suited for:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Fixed-format workflows</li>
        <li>Reusable writing templates</li>
        <li>Form-style task launchers</li>
        <li>"Help me draft something" patterns with clear input fields</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For example, parameterized prompt templates like:
      </p>
      <ul class="uri-list">
        <li><code>draft_reflection_post(topic, audience)</code></li>
        <li><code>prepare_meeting_summary(meeting_name, tone)</code></li>
        <li><code>generate_progress_report(project_name, deadline)</code></li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          If a tool is the "hand," and a resource is the "reference folder," then a prompt is more like the "<strong>work instructions</strong>."
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Notion classroom breakdown -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Walking Through a Notion Classroom Knowledge Base</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For one and the same system, <strong>different capabilities should actually go to different places</strong>. Suppose you have a Notion classroom knowledge base meant to support students working on their final projects. We can pull the three kinds of capability apart in one go:
      </p>

      <ol class="breakdown-list">
        <li class="breakdown-item breakdown-item--resource">
          <p class="breakdown-tag">resource</p>
          <p class="breakdown-name"><code>course://rubric/final-project</code></p>
          <p class="breakdown-desc">
            Because it's a <strong>grading rubric</strong> — essentially background data, meant to be read by the model and looked up by humans, not to take action.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="breakdown-item breakdown-item--prompt">
          <p class="breakdown-tag">prompt</p>
          <p class="breakdown-name"><code>draft_reflection_post(topic, audience)</code></p>
          <p class="breakdown-desc">
            Because it's a <strong>fixed-format task template</strong>. You provide a topic and audience, and it generates a structured drafting flow.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="breakdown-item breakdown-item--tool">
          <p class="breakdown-tag">tool</p>
          <p class="breakdown-name"><code>create_page(title, content)</code></p>
          <p class="breakdown-desc">
            Because it <strong>actually creates a page</strong>. It performs an action on an external system, which is a great fit for a tool.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          Once you split it this way, the design becomes very clear:<br/>
          <strong>Data is data, templates are templates, actions are actions.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Decision tree -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">A Quick Decision Tree</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        When you encounter a new capability, you can step through these three questions in order:
      </p>

      <ol class="decision-list">
        <li class="decision-item">
          <span class="decision-num">Q1</span>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <p class="decision-question">Will it actually modify an external system?</p>
            <p class="decision-answer">If yes, lean toward <strong>tool</strong>.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="decision-item">
          <span class="decision-num">Q2</span>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <p class="decision-question">Is it mainly providing background data?</p>
            <p class="decision-answer">If yes, lean toward <strong>resource</strong>.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="decision-item">
          <span class="decision-num">Q3</span>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <p class="decision-question">Is it mainly providing a fixed format or workflow template?</p>
            <p class="decision-answer">If yes, lean toward <strong>prompt</strong>.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          <strong>What if it's a bit of all three?</strong> Then split it smaller first. <strong>Don't try to cram three jobs into one thing.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Relation to previous page -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">How This Page Differs From the Previous One</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        These two pages are connected, but they aren't saying the same thing:
      </p>

      <div class="relation-grid">
        <article class="relation-card relation-card--prev">
          <p class="relation-card__label">PREVIOUS PAGE</p>
          <p class="relation-card__theme">Don't open too many capabilities</p>
          <p class="relation-card__desc">Don't hand AI too many tools all at once.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="relation-card relation-card--this">
          <p class="relation-card__label">THIS PAGE</p>
          <p class="relation-card__theme">Don't mix kinds of capabilities</p>
          <p class="relation-card__desc">Even with only a few capabilities open, separate which ones are tools, which are resources, and which are prompts.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .ai-agent-primitives {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .detail-subtitle strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Sub-heading inside a section */
  .sub-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-left: var(--space-3);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
  }

  /* Inline code */
  :global(.detail-paragraph) code,
  :global(.detail-subtitle) code,
  :global(.check-list) code,
  :global(.cross-list) code,
  :global(.callout-text) code,
  :global(.highlight-text) code,
  :global(.misuse-desc) code,
  :global(.decision-question) code,
  :global(.decision-answer) code {
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  /* Check list */
  .check-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .check-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .check-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Cross list (✗ items) */
  .cross-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .cross-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .cross-list li::before {
    content: '\2717';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Callout card */
  .callout-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-8);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .callout-text {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .callout-text strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Highlight card (key takeaway) */
  .highlight-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .highlight-card--strong {
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border-width: 2px;
  }

  .highlight-text {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .highlight-text strong {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Primitive grid (tool / resource / prompt) */
  .primitive-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .primitive-card {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 2px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    text-align: center;
    transition: transform var(--transition);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-2);
  }

  .primitive-card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .primitive-card__icon {
    margin: 0 auto var(--space-2);
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    line-height: 1;
    width: 3rem;
    height: 3rem;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .primitive-card__tag {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin: 0;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
  }

  .primitive-card__name {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .primitive-card__name code {
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 1em;
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .primitive-card__role {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .primitive-card__desc {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .primitive-card__desc strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Misuse list (3 anti-patterns) */
  .misuse-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-6);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
  }

  .misuse-item {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-text-muted);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
  }

  .misuse-body {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .misuse-title {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-1);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .misuse-desc {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .misuse-desc code {
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-tag-text);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .misuse-tag {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    padding: var(--space-1) var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #fff;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    letter-spacing: 0.03em;
  }

  /* URI list (URI-style examples) */
  .uri-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    margin: var(--space-3) 0 var(--space-6);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px dashed var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-2);
  }

  .uri-list li {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-heading);
  }

  .uri-list li code {
    padding: 0.15em 0.5em;
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    font-size: 1em;
  }

  /* Breakdown list (Notion classroom split) */
  .breakdown-list {
